mall-Town Movie Theaters -- t14.Conclusion: When Theory Hits The Road -- tContributors -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHollywood in the Neighborhood presents a vivid new picture of how movies entered the American heartland—the thousands of smaller cities, towns, and villages far from the East and West Coast film centers. Using a broad range of research sources, essays from scholars including Richard Abel, Robert Allen, Kathryn Fuller-Seeley, Terry Lindvall, and Greg Waller examine in detail the social and cultural changes this new form of entertainment brought to towns from Gastonia, North Carolina to Placerville, California, and from Norfolk, Virginia to rural Ontario and beyond. Emphasizing the roles of local exhibitors, neighborhood audiences, regional cultures, and the growing national mass media, their essays chart how motion pictures so quickly and successfully moved into old opera houses and glittering new picture palaces on Main Streets across America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMotion picture audienceszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMotion picture theaterszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  a20th century american films.  aamerican audiences.  aamerican films.  aamerican heartland.  aamerican midwest.  aearly film exhibition.  aentertainment industry.  aethnography.  afilm audiences.  afilm industry.  afilm studies.  afilm.  agovernment film exhibition.  agreat depression.  ahistory of hollywood.  ahistory.  ahollywood.  alocal moviegoing.  amedia studies.  amotion pictures.  amovie show.  amovie studies.  amovies.  anational mass media.  apolitical.  ara